Well-armed Achaeans, for their part, led Ajax,\uc0\u8232 elated by his victory, to lord Agamemnon.\u8232 When they all came inside the son of Atreus\'92 hut,\u8232 Agamemnon, king of men, sacrificed an ox,\u8232 a male five years old, to the exalted son of Cronos.\u8232 They flayed the beast, prepared and carved it up,\u8232 chopping it skilfully into tiny pieces.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0370\u8232 They skewered these on spits, cooked them carefully,\u8232 and drew them off. This done, they prepared a meal and ate.\u8232 No one went unsatisfied. All feasted equally.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[320]\u8232 Wide-ruling Agamemnon, heroic son of Atreus,\u8232 acknowledged Ajax with the whole back cut of meat.\u8232 When everyone had had his fill of food and drink,\u8232 old Nestor spoke up first, outlining for them\u8232 a plan he had. Earlier his advice had seemed the best.\u8232 Keeping in mind their common good, he said:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Son of Atreus, you other Argive leaders,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0380\uc0\u8232 many long-haired Achaeans have been killed.\u8232 Fierce Ares has scattered their dark blood\u8232 beside the fair-flowing Scamander river.\u8232 Their souls have departed down to Hades.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[330]\u8232 So tomorrow you should call a halt.\u8232 Stop Achaeans fighting. We should all assemble,\u8232 then carry off the bodies of the dead\u8232 with mules and oxen. Then we\'92ll burn them\u8232 a short distance from our ships, so each of us,\u8232 when we return, may carry back the bones.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0390\u8232 Let\'92s set up one single common funeral mound\u8232 close by the fire and angled on the plain.\u8232 Then with all speed from that mound we\'92ll build\u8232 some high walls with turrets, to guard us and our ships.\u8232 In those walls we\'92ll construct tight-fitting gates,\u8232 so there\'92s a path to drive our chariots through.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[340]\u8232 Outside we\'92ll dig a deep trench close beside it,\u8232 to enclose the walls and hold out chariots\'97\u8232 soldiers, too, if those impetuous Trojans\u8232 should ever drive us back in battle.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0400\
